   "sections":[
      {
         "name":"A",
         "description":"Multiple Choice, True/False, and Fill-in-the-Blank Questions",
         "questions":[
            {
               "questionNumber":1,
               "text":"Fill in the blanks using the most appropriate term from the box below. Each term may be used once or not at all.",
               "type":"fill-in-blank",
               "points":3,
               "subQuestions":[
                  {
                     "label":"a)",
                     "text":"A ................................ is a magnet made from a coil of wire carrying an electric current wound around an iron core.",
                     "type":"fill-in-blank",
                     "correctAnswer":"Electromagnet",
                     "points":1
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"b)",
                     "text":"A ................................ is a cylindrical coil of wire that acts as a magnet when electric current flows through it.",
                     "type":"fill-in-blank",
                     "correctAnswer":"Solenoid",
                     "points":1
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"c)",
                     "text":"When a conductor moves through a magnetic field, a(n) ................................ is produced in the conductor.",
                     "type":"fill-in-blank",
                     "correctAnswer":"Induced EMF",
                     "points":1
                  }
               ]
            },
            {
               "questionNumber":2,
               "text":"Choose the letter of the best answer for each question.",
               "type":"multiple-choice",
               "points":4,
               "subQuestions":[
                  {
                     "label":"a)",
                     "text":"Which of the following best describes the term 'noise' in a communication system?",
                     "type":"multiple-choice",
                     "options":[
                        {
                           "letter":"i",
                           "text":"The loudness of the transmitted signal",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "letter":"ii",
                           "text":"Any unwanted disturbance that interferes with the transmitted signal",
                           "isCorrect":true
                        },
                        {
                           "letter":"iii",
                           "text":"The frequency at which the signal is transmitted",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "letter":"iv",
                           "text":"The distance between the transmitter and receiver",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        }
                     ],
                     "correctAnswer":"ii",
                     "points":1
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"b)",
                     "text":"Which electronic component allows current to flow in only one direction?",
                     "type":"multiple-choice",
                     "options":[
                        {
                           "letter":"i",
                           "text":"Transistor",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "letter":"ii",
                           "text":"Resistor",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "letter":"iii",
                           "text":"Capacitor",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "letter":"iv",
                           "text":"Diode",
                           "isCorrect":true
                        }
                     ],
                     "correctAnswer":"iv",
                     "points":1
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"c)",
                     "text":"In a transistor used as a switch, the transistor is said to be in saturation when it is:",
                     "type":"multiple-choice",
                     "options":[
                        {
                           "letter":"i",
                           "text":"fully off",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "letter":"ii",
                           "text":"partially on",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "letter":"iii",
                           "text":"fully on",
                           "isCorrect":true
                        },
                        {
                           "letter":"iv",
                           "text":"in reverse bias",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        }
                     ],
                     "correctAnswer":"iii",
                     "points":1
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"d)",
                     "text":"Which type of wave is used in mobile phone communication?",
                     "type":"multiple-choice",
                     "options":[
                        {
                           "letter":"i",
                           "text":"Sound waves",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "letter":"ii",
                           "text":"Infrared waves",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        },
                        {
                           "letter":"iii",
                           "text":"Radio waves / Microwaves",
                           "isCorrect":true
                        },
                        {
                           "letter":"iv",
                           "text":"X-rays",
                           "isCorrect":false
                        }
                     ],
                     "correctAnswer":"iii",
                     "points":1
                  }
               ]
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "name":"B",
         "description":"Short Answer Questions",
         "questions":[
            {
               "questionNumber":16,
               "text":"Refraction is the bending of light as it passes from one medium to another.",
               "type":"open-ended",
               "points":10,
               "subQuestions":[
                  {
                     "label":"a)",
                     "text":"State Snell's Law of refraction and write its mathematical expression.",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "correctAnswer":"Snell's Law: n₁ sinθ₁ = n₂ sinθ₂",
                     "points":2
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"b)",
                     "text":"A ray of light travels from air into a glass block. The angle of incidence is 45° and the refractive index of the glass is 1.5. Calculate the angle of refraction.",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "correctAnswer":"28.1°",
                     "points":3
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"c)",
                     "text":"Draw a clearly labelled ray diagram showing the refraction of light as it passes from air into a denser glass block. Include the normal line, angles of incidence and refraction.",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "correctAnswer":"Ray diagram",
                     "points":3
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"d)",
                     "text":"Define the term 'critical angle' and state the condition under which total internal reflection occurs.",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "correctAnswer":"Critical angle: the angle of incidence in the denser medium at which the refracted ray travels along the interface",
                     "points":2
                  }
               ]
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "name":"C",
         "description":"Essay/Long Answer Questions",
         "questions":[
            {
               "questionNumber":21,
               "text":"A student investigates how the extension of a spring depends on the load applied to it.",
               "type":"open-ended",
               "points":15,
               "subQuestions":[
                  {
                     "label":"a)",
                     "text":"Complete the third column by converting each extension value from centimetres to metres.",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "correctAnswer":"0.020 m; 0.040 m; 0.060 m; 0.080 m; 0.100 m; 0.120 m",
                     "points":2
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"b)",
                     "text":"State the law that describes the relationship between force and extension for a spring within its elastic limit.",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "correctAnswer":"Hooke's Law: F = ke",
                     "points":2
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"c)",
                     "text":"Plot a graph of Load (y-axis) against Extension in metres (x-axis) on the provided graph paper. Draw the best-fit straight line.",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "correctAnswer":"Graph",
                     "points":6
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"d)",
                     "text":"i) From your graph, determine the slope (gradient) of the line and state its physical meaning. ii) Calculate the spring constant k, including its unit.",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "correctAnswer":"i) 50 N/m, ii) 50 N/m",
                     "points":3
                  },
                  {
                     "label":"e)",
                     "text":"If a load of 3.5 N is applied to the spring, predict the extension using your graph or formula.",
                     "type":"open-ended",
                     "correctAnswer":"0.07 m",
                     "points":2
                  }
               ]
            }
         ]
      }
   ]
